gomodel:SYNGO_2102  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.2: \"Recycling Endosome Transport into Dendritic Spines Depends Actin and on MT Dynamics\"\n- Literal: \"We frequently observed Rab11 vesicles containing GFP-GluA2 in dendritic spines (Figure 2A; Movie S2). Under basal conditions, GFP-GluA2-positive Rab11 vesicles moved in and out of spines (Figures 2B and S2A). The recycling endosomes that entered spines did not necessarily emerge from immobile storage sites near the spine base, but frequently moved from distant dendritic regions\". Experimental description: - \"Primary hippocampal cultures were prepared from embryonic day 18 (E18) rat brains\"\n- The localization of Rab11a is tracked via overexpressed Rab11a provided by the Hoogenraad lab. The Hoogenraad lab was contacted for species information (Casper Hoogenraad [c.hoogenraad@uu.nl]; Harold MacGillavry [H.D.MacGillavry@uu.nl], dd 12/12/2017). Authors answered: \"Beste Pirm, we gebruiken human Rab11a in deze paper. Groeten Casper\"\n- Annotation was made against human species" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5615-1014" ;
        dc:date           "2017-12-19" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_2102" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_9606" .

